---
import PNotes from "../components/PNotes.astro";
---

<p-slide class="cover-internal">
  <h1>The near future</h1>

  <PNotes>
    <p>This section is honest speculation, not "use this Monday".</p>
    <p>
      The point is not production readiness. The point is direction: CSS is
      moving conditional logic closer to values and components.
    </p>
    <p>
      Set expectations up front — these are real ideas, some shipping or nearly
      shipping, but always check support before building on them.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide class="cover-internal-sub-section">
  <h2>Style queries</h2>

  <PNotes>
    <p>Container queries, but querying a custom property instead of size.</p>
    <p>
      Size queries ask: how much room do I have? Style queries ask: what state
      or tone did my container expose?
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3 class="main-gradient">Variants without extra classes</h3>
  <ul>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🚫 <span>No </span><span class="main-sub-gradient">modifier class</span
      ><span> just to express a variant</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      🌗 <span>The container's </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >state</span
      ><span> drives the styling</span>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      The idea: the container exposes a value, like --tone: loud, and its
      children react to it.
    </p>
    <p>
      The variant becomes data in CSS, not another naming convention to keep in
      sync.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Query a custom property</span> 🎛️
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="style-query.css">
  <code style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-scss">section {
        --tone: muted; /* just data on the container */
    }
    /* children react to the container's property */
    @container style(--tone: muted) {
        article {
            background: oklch(0.95 0.02 250);
        }
    }
    @container style(--tone: loud) {
        article {
            background: oklch(0.7 0.2 250);
            color: white;
        }
    }</code></pre>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Every element is implicitly a style container — no container-type needed
      for style queries, unlike size queries. Worth saying.
    </p>
    <p>
      Gotcha to flag: today style queries work on custom properties, not regular
      CSS properties. Don't oversell it.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is still progressive-enhancement territory: useful, interesting, but
      check the support table before relying on it as your only styling path.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide support>
  <h3 class="main-gradient">About support</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      ✅ <span class="main-sub-gradient">Chrome, Edge, Safari</span><span>
        — shipping for custom properties</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🦊 <span>Firefox support </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >is moving</span
      ><span> — verify the table</span>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Be precise here. Credibility comes from saying what works, what does not,
      and where the edges are.
    </p>
    <p>
      The progressive-enhancement line is the responsible takeaway: it's a bonus
      layer, not a foundation for every project yet.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide class="cover-internal-sub-section">
  <h2>if()</h2>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Be precise: this is the if() function, inline in a value — not a block
      @if.
    </p>
    <p>
      @when/@else are further out: spec-level ideas, no browser ships them as a
      practical authoring tool today.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3 class="main-gradient">Inline conditional values</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      🔀 <span>Pick a value </span><span class="main-sub-gradient">inline</span
      ><span>, inside one declaration</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      📏 <span>One </span><span class="main-sub-gradient">property value</span
      ><span> at a time — not whole blocks</span>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Frame the difference vs @container: if() sets a single value; @container
      applies a whole rule set.
    </p>
    <p>
      They are complementary, not rivals: one is inline value selection, the
      other is conditional rule application.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">if() — a value, conditionally</span> 🔀
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="if-function.css">
    <code style="font-size: 0.7em" is:raw class="language-scss">
    section {
        --tone: loud;
    }

    article {
        background: if(
            style(--tone: loud): oklch(0.7 0.2 250);
            else: oklch(0.95 0.02 250)
        );
    }</code>
  </pre>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Read it as: if the container exposes --tone: loud, use the loud
      background; otherwise use the muted background.
    </p>
    <p>
      Same idea as the style query slide, but now the conditional choice happens
      inside one property value.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is genuinely young syntax — say it. It's the most forward-looking
      thing in the talk.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide support>
  <h3 class="main-gradient">About support</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      🧪 <span class="main-sub-gradient">if()</span><span>
        — young support, Chromium 137+</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      📏 <span>Inline </span><span class="main-sub-gradient">values only</span
      ><span> — not rule blocks</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      🌱 <span>Worth </span><span class="main-sub-gradient">watching</span><span
        >, not betting on</span
      >
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      The third bullet pre-empts the audience member who saw an @if or @when
      proposal somewhere. Set the record straight kindly.
    </p>
    <p>
      Close honestly: this is where CSS is heading — bookmark it, don't bet a
      production design system on it yet.
    </p>
    <p>Transition into the summary map, then the honest limits.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<style lang="scss">
  [support] {
    li {
      margin-block-end: 0.3em;
    }
  }
</style>
